reviews.review: A great movie and it's  for who made star wars be what it is... their fans, not the critics.

Great movie! A really great ending to an amazing saga. It gives clarity to a lot of things, while also giving potholes to those fans who love the comics! For those who aren't as involved, it could be a small amount confusing, but the story is indeed worth even the time of the fans who aren't as involved with the saga. It continued the love and action, in depth story  and awe aspects from the previous six movies, but brought a fresher story. Whether you're a Prequels fan, a O.T fan, or a sequels fan, this is a must watch Star Wars Movie!
It wasn't perfect, of course. But it just had everything and everyone, and my heart is happy.

This whole trilogy was a narrative mess. Lesson be told do not create a trilogy without an overarching story in mind through all 3 movies ESPECIALLY when you are doing a sequel trilogy to the most iconic trilogy of all time in the original Star Wars movies. I could always rewatch the original Star Wars and I could always go back and re-watch the 4 phases of the Marvel universe. However, I don’t look forward to going back and re-visiting this trilogy This movie felt like one big rollercoaster ride. It was entertaining but you don’t feel attached to anything going on because everything is moving so fast to wrap up the loose ends Abrams created in Force Awakens while creating huge plot holes that leave us with new unanswered questions. Scorsese should’ve made his comments against this movie but not Marvel. At least Marvel had planned narratives from point A to B and character building and it lands in its final installment of Endgame. When Endgame was over there was loud clapping, you felt the emotion in the audience, people were crying, and all the big moments were earned and executed well. At the end of the showing opening night in my theater, there were few awkward claps, no emotion felt, people were sitting there unsure what to think and all the big moments were not earned and weightless. This movie seriously felt like a 90s action movie of story telling. A lot of action but weird weird decisions and lazy story telling. The only good things in this was all the acting (Daisy Ridley is outstanding), the music, and the cinematography. Other than that, this in-cohesive trilogy should’ve been left in a galaxy far far away.
As a true Star Wars geek who loved both the originals and prequels, I liked this movie. It fixed what the Last Jedi did wrong, and brought this trilogy to a satisfying ending (for the most part).
Very nice way to end the saga!

The sense that his movie exists solely to write out The Last Jedi never stops being a prominent theme until the very end.  The frantic undoing and rebuilding of the story Rian Johnson created to fit JJ Abrams's bland tunnel vision made the whole experience unpleasant.  

All of the unique elements brought into the Star Wars universe were sacrificed to build a narrative that once again follows the same story beats of the original trilogy.  However, unlike The Force Awakens, there wasn't any room left for a fun romp through the Star Wars universe.  It was just waves of scene transitions designed to move the audience to the next abandonment of the established story.
Pulls the franchise together nicely, ignore the critics.  Fans of the franchise will enjoy themselves

I think it is my 2nd favorite Star Wars film just behind "The Empire Strikes Back". It was not a perfect movie by any stretch, filled with lots of decisions to course correct the current trilogy, but I did feel like a little kid again. I cried several times and walked out of the theater smiling, proud to be a Star Wars fan. Thank you J.J. Abrams for telling us a fitting end to the Skywalker Saga.
